# <%= projectName %>

Next.js 16 BFF (Backend-for-Frontend) service. This is an **API-only** project — no React pages, no UI. It sits between your frontend apps and your backend microservices, handling auth, request validation, response transformation, and error normalization.

## Getting Started

```bash
# Install dependencies
npm install

# Start the dev server (http://localhost:3000)
npm run dev
```

Once running, try these endpoints:

| Endpoint | Method | What It Does |
|----------|--------|-------------|
| `/api/health` | GET | Returns `{ status: "UP" }` — use for liveness probes |
| `/api/health/ready` | GET | Checks downstream services — use for readiness probes |
| `/api/sample` | GET | Lists sample items (supports `?page=1&limit=10`) |
| `/api/sample` | POST | Creates a new sample item |
| `/api/sample/:id` | GET | Gets a single sample item |
| `/api/sample/:id` | PUT | Updates a sample item |
| `/api/sample/:id` | DELETE | Deletes a sample item |

The `/api/sample` endpoints are a **working example** of the full BFF pattern. Use them as a reference when building your own routes, then delete them when you no longer need them.

