## How the BFF Pattern Works

Every route follows the same flow:

```
Incoming request
  → proxy.ts (adds correlation ID, checks auth, sets security headers)
  → Route handler (validates request with Zod)
  → Client (calls backend service with auth + retry + logging)
  → Mapper (transforms backend response to frontend shape)
  → Response sent to frontend
```

**Route handlers** validate and orchestrate. They never call backends directly or contain business logic.

**Clients** handle HTTP communication with backend services. One client per service. They add auth tokens, correlation IDs, retry failed requests, and log everything.

**Mappers** transform data. Backend shapes go in, frontend shapes come out. This is the only place where response transformation happens.

## Adding a New Route

Say you need to add an `/api/accounts` endpoint that talks to an accounts backend service.

### 1. Define the types

```
types/
  api/accounts.ts        # What your frontend receives
  backend/accounts.ts    # What the accounts service returns
```

### 2. Create the client

```
clients/accounts-client.ts   # HTTP calls to the accounts service
```

Copy `sample-client.ts` and change the base URL and methods.

### 3. Create the mapper

```
mappers/account-mapper.ts    # Backend shape → frontend shape
```

### 4. Create the route

```
app/api/accounts/route.ts          # GET (list), POST (create)
app/api/accounts/[id]/route.ts     # GET (single), PUT, DELETE
```

### 5. Add tests

```
tests/accounts-client.test.ts
tests/account-mapper.test.ts
tests/accounts-route.test.ts
mocks/handlers/accounts-handlers.ts
```

